ce:section.ce:para:
The pyrolysis method was used to synthesize green CDs by selecting an optimal molar ratio of urea and tri-sodium citrate (1:1). The CDs were obtained with a product yield of 45.5 % and a concentration of 2 g/L. Green CDs display an absorption peak within the UV–visible spectrum. The absorption in the 230–270 nm range is attributed to the π-π∗ transition of CC, while the absorption in the 300–330 nm range is due to the n-π∗ transition of CO. The UV absorption of CDs is influenced by surface functional groups that have strong absorption at specific wavelengths [41–43]. To investigate the formation of the CDs, a UV–Vis absorption measurement was conducted. As depicted in Fig. 1
                        A, the absorption peaks for the aqueous solutions of CDs were observed at under 450 nm. Notably, the CDs-anti Nanog exhibited a highly conspicuous absorption peak at approximately 270 nm, indicating successful labeling of the Nanog antibody onto the CDs. The resulting CDs and CDs-Ab2 displayed a bright green color that was easily discernible under UV illumination, as observed by the naked eye (Fig. 1A, inset). CDs were produced using a straightforward, convenient, one-step process involving trisodium citrate and urea. In Fig. 1B, it is demonstrated that the fluorescent emission peak of CDs shifts to a different wavelength with changes in the excitation wavelength. This responsive characteristic indicates the influence of varying sizes [13]. The excitation wavelength of 400 nm was selected as it corresponded to the maximum emission intensity. The excitation and emission spectra of CDs and CDs-Ab2 were identical as shown in Fig. 1C. CDs and CDs-Ab2 showed a noticeable emission band centered at 550 nm upon excitation at 400 nm. The morphology and nanostructure of carbon dots were analyzed using transmission electron microscopy (TEM). As shown in Fig. 1Da, the carbon dots displayed spherical-shaped particles with an average size of around 5 nm. The carbon dots obtained have different sizes, ranging from 2 to 6 nm (Fig. 1Db). A long-term homogeneous phase is observed in green-emitting CDs obtained in an aqueous state at room temperature, which does not show sedimentation. The high density of functional groups on the surface of the CDs can introduce surface traps, enabling the facile conjugation of a large amount of anti-Nanog antibodies, as a result, The target became more readily detectable, due to its beneficial functional groups (–COOH, –NH2, and –OH). Fourier-transform infrared (FTIR) analysis was performed to investigate the chemical compositions and the surface functional groups of the carbon dots (Fig. 2
                        ). The FTIR spectrum of CDs exhibited stretching vibrations of C–OH at 3441 cm−1 and asymmetric stretching vibrations of C–NH–C at 1116 cm−1. The carboxylate anions (–COO–) asymmetric and symmetric stretching vibrations are responsible for the strong peaks observed at 1595 cm−1 and 1389 cm−1, respectively. Broadening of peaks in the CD-Ab2 spectrum around 3441 cm−1, 2156-2327 cm−1, and 1649 cm−1 is attributed to N–H, C  N, and CO stretching, respectively. These findings suggest that the treatment of CDs with EDC/NHS and anti-Nanog resulted in the introduction of numerous carboxyl groups and an increase in O–H and N–H stretching vibrations. Furthermore, characteristic bands associated with –CONH– were observed around 1649 cm−1 and 1598 cm−1, indicating the successful conjugation of the Nanog antibody onto the CDs [44,45].
